[
    {
        "content": "<p>In '<em>Higher Topos Theory in Physics</em>', Urs points out that linearity means <em>abelian group structure</em> and in higher gauge theory.</p>\n<p>Ignoring all the physics for the moment, and sticking to linear algebra, how exactly does linear structure come about by delooping, and what is the exact relation between abelian/symmetric structure and linearity?</p>\n<p>I mean, I doubt many people think of linear algebra as being about abelian structure, at least not it the immediate. Can someone make this a bit more explicit as to what is going on?</p>",
        "id": 508360086,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Elliott Peterson",
        "timestamp": 1743016758
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's an important classical theorem that infinite loop spaces are the same as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E_\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0576em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-spaces, which are spaces with a multiplication operation that's infinitely coherently homotopy-associative and -commutative. Does that answer the first question?</p>",
        "id": 508370899,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1743020691
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't really know a precise notion of \"linearity\" that's relevant to compare to \"abelian/symmetric\" structure, other than that words like \"linear\" are often used as rough synonyms for stability, which is the property of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-categories in which delooping is an auto-equivalence, which in particular gives every object an internal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E_\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0576em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∞</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-structure.</p>",
        "id": 508371222,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1743020816
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Keith wrote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I mean, I doubt many people think of linear algebra as being about abelian structure, at least not it the immediate.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Most ordinary folks think about linear algebra as being about vector spaces, but many important features of linear algebra generalize to modules of an arbitrary commutative ring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>, and when we take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R = \\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> these are none other than abelian groups.   That's the simplest reason why \"abelian\" and \"linear algebra\" sound very similar to Urs (and me).   </p>\n<p>Next, the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>-modules for any ring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> is an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/abelian%20category\">[[abelian category]]</a>.    </p>\n<p>Then comes the relation to delooping, but I'm out of time for now!</p>\n<p>So when Urs is talking about \"linearity\" he's talking about</p>",
        "id": 508639604,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1743119945
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What a cliffhanger.</p>",
        "id": 508664096,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1743134963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One way to see the proximity between the spectral side and linearity is through a construction known as the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/t-structure\">[[heart]]</a>, which picks out the \"0-sector\" of  stable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-categories. E.g., the heart of the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H \\mathbb{K}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">K</span></span></span></span> module spectra is the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{K}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">K</span></span></span></span>-vector spaces. You can see these module spectra as a kind of categorified vector space. </p>\n<p>I was having an idle <a href=\"https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/15290/hermitian-form/?Focus=121075#Comment_121075\">wonder</a> about \"truncations\" to larger sections via other t-structures. Couldn't we see <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span>'s Baez-Crans 2-vector spaces appear?</p>",
        "id": 508686584,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1743147747
    }
]